<subSubSection pageId="674" pageNumber="675" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="674" pageNumber="675">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Triliarthrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="674" pageNumber="675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Triliarthrus</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1914: 238. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haldeman" authorityYear="1843" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Stenolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="674" pageNumber="675" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="badipennis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="674" pageNumber="675">Stenolophus badipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Haldeman, 1843 designated by Lindroth (1968: 898). Etymology. Probably from the Greek prefix 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="674" pageNumber="675">tri</emphasis>
- (three), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="674" pageNumber="675">lis</emphasis>
(smooth), and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="674" pageNumber="675">arthron</emphasis>
(joint), alluding to the glabrous antennomeres 1-3 of the adults (&quot;the first three joints of the antennae are glabrous&quot;) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
